{{hatnote|'Ear of wheat' redirects here. Not to be confused with '[[wheatear]]'  which is a kind of bird that has a white vent.}}
[[File:Getreide.jpg|thumb|250px|Unripe ears of [[barley]], [[wheat]], and [[rye]].]]

An '''ear''' is the [[grain]]-bearing tip part of the [[plant stem|stem]] of a [[cereal]] plant, such as [[wheat]] or [[maize]].<ref>{{cite book|page=121|title=A Glossary of Botanic Terms with their Derivation and Accent|last=Jackson|first=Benjamin Daydon|edition=fourth|publisher=Gerald Duckworth & Co. Ltd.|location=London|year=1928|url=https://archive.org/details/glossaryofbotani1928jack}}</ref>  It can also refer to "a prominent lobe in some leaves".<ref name="Swartz">{{cite book|page=162|title=Collegiate Dictionary of Botany|last=Swartz|first=Delbert|publisher=The Ronald Press Company|location=New York|year=1971}}</ref>

The ear is a [[Spike (botany)|spike]], consisting of a central stem on which tightly packed rows of [[flower]]s grow.  These develop into [[fruit]]s containing the edible [[seed]]s. In corn, it is protected by leaves called husks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lerner|first=Rosie|title=Corn - Ears|url=http://www.hort.purdue.edu/ext/senior/vegetabl/corn1.htm|work=Senior Study Vegetables|publisher=Purdue University|accessdate=2012-05-24}}</ref>

In some species (including wheat), un[[ripening|ripe]] ears contribute significantly to photosynthesis, in addition to the [[leaf|leaves]] lower down the plant.

A parasite known as ''[[Anguina tritici]]'' (Ear Cockle) specifically affects the ears on wheat and rye by destroying the tissues and stems during growth. With the exception of North Africa and West Asia, the parasite has been eradicated in all countries by using the 
[[crop rotation]] system.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ear Cockle Disease of Wheat|url=http://agrihunt.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=364|publisher=Agrihunt|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref>

